# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cost-optimization-cloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] In computing, **elasticity** is defined as "the degree to which a system is able to adapt to workload changes by provisioning and de-provisioning resources in an autonomic manner, such that at each point in time the available resources match the current demand as closely as possible".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity is a defining characteristic that differentiates cloud computing from previously proposed distributed computing paradigms, such as grid computing.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] The dynamic adaptation of capacity, e.g., by altering the use of computing resources, to meet a varying workload is called "elastic computing".
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] In the world of distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors; some consider the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity aims to match the amount of resources allocated to a service with the amount of resources it actually requires, avoiding over- or under-provisioning.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] **Over-provisioning**, i.e., allocating more resources than required, should be avoided as it may incur extra costs (monetary, energy, operational, etc.) for unused or underutilized resources.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] For example, if a website is over-provisioned with two cloud computing resources to handle current demand that only requires one resource, the costs of maintaining the second resource would effectively be wasted.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elasticity can be illustrated through an example of a service provider who wants to run a website on the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] At moment $t_{0}$ , the website is unpopular and a single machine is sufficient to serve all users.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] At moment $t_{1}$ , the website suddenly becomes popular, and a single machine is no longer sufficient to serve all users.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Based on the number of web users simultaneously accessing the website and the resource requirements of the web server, ten machines are needed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and provision nine additional machines from the cloud to serve all users responsively.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] At time $t_{2}$ , the website becomes unpopular again.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] The ten machines currently allocated to the website are mostly idle and a single machine would be sufficient to serve the few users who are accessing the website.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] An elastic system should immediately detect this condition and deprovision nine machines, releasing them to the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] A cloud virtual machine (VM) can be acquired at any time by the user; however, it may take up to several minutes for the acquired VM to be ready to use.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] The VM startup time is dependent on factors such as image size, VM type, data center location, number of VMs, etc.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Cloud providers have different VM startup performance.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] This implies that any control mechanism designed for elastic applications must consider the time needed for the resource provisioning actions to take effect.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elastic applications can allocate and deallocate resources on demand for specific application components.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] This makes cloud resources volatile, and traditional monitoring tools which associate monitoring data with a particular resource, such as Ganglia or Nagios, are no longer suitable for monitoring the *behavior* of elastic applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] For example, during its lifetime, a data storage tier of an elastic application might add and remove data storage VMs due to cost and performance requirements, varying the number of used VMs.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Thus, additional information is needed in monitoring elastic applications, such as associating the logical application structure over the underlying virtual infrastructure.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] When deploying applications in cloud infrastructures (IaaS/PaaS), stakeholder requirements need to be considered in order to ensure that elastic behavior meets stakeholder needs.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Traditionally, the optimal trade-off between cost and quality or performance is considered; however, for real world cloud users, requirements regarding elastic behavior are more complex and target multiple dimensions of elasticity (e.g., SYBL).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Cloud applications vary in type and complexity, with multiple levels of artifacts deployed in layers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Controlling such structures must take into consideration a variety of issues.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] Elastic strategies on in cloud computing can take advantage of control-theoretic methods (e.g., predictive control has been experimented in cloud computing scenarios by showing considerable advantages with respect to reactive methods).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/elasticity-cloud-computing] One approach to multi-level elastic clouc control is rSYBL.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In computer programming, **resource management** refers to techniques for managing resources (components with limited availability).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Computer programs may manage their own resources by using features exposed by programming languages (Elder, Jackson & Liblit (2008) is a survey article contrasting different approaches), or may elect to manage them by a host – an operating system or virtual machine – or another program.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Host-based management is known as *resource tracking,* and consists of cleaning up resource leaks: terminating access to resources that have been acquired but not released after use.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is known as *reclaiming* resources, and is analogous to garbage collection for memory.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] On many systems, the operating system reclaims resources after the process makes the exit system call.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] The omission of releasing a resource when a program has finished using it is known as a resource leak, and is an issue in sequential computing.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Multiple processes wish to access a limited resource can be an issue in concurrent computing, and is known as resource contention.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Resource management seeks to control access in order to prevent both of these situations.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Formally, resource management (preventing resource leaks) consists of ensuring that a resource is released if and only if it is successfully acquired.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This general problem can be abstracted as "*before,* *body,* and *after*" code, which normally are executed in this order, with the condition that the *after* code is called if and only if the *before* code successfully completes, regardless of whether the *body* code executes successfully or not.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is also known as *execute around* or a *code sandwich,* and occurs in various other contexts, such as a temporary change of program state, or tracing entry and exit into a subroutine.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, resource management is the most commonly cited application.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In aspect-oriented programming, such execute around logic is a form of *advice*.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In the terminology of control flow analysis, resource release must postdominate successful resource acquisition; failure to ensure this is a bug, and a code path that violates this condition causes a resource leak.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are often minor problems, generally not crashing the program, but instead causing some slowdown to the program or the overall system.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, they may cause crashes – either the program itself or other programs – due to *resource exhaustion:* if the system runs out of resources, acquisition requests fail.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This can present a security bug if an attack can cause resource exhaustion.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks may happen under regular program flow – such as simply forgetting to release a resource – or only in exceptional circumstances, such as when a resource is not released if there is an exception in another part of the program.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are very frequently caused by early exit from a subroutine, either by a `return` statement, or an exception raised either by the subroutine itself, or a deeper subroutine that it calls.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] While resource release due to return statements can be handled by carefully releasing within the subroutine before the return, exceptions cannot be handled without some additional language facility that guarantees that release code is executed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] More subtly, successful resource acquisition must dominate resource release, as otherwise the code will try to release a resource it has not acquired.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] The consequences of such an incorrect release range from being silently ignored to crashing the program or unpredictable behavior.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] These bugs generally manifest rarely, as they require resource allocation to first fail, which is generally an exceptional case.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Further, the consequences may not be serious, as the program may already be crashing due to failure to acquire an essential resource.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, these can prevent recovery from the failure, or turn an orderly shutdown into a disorderly shutdown.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In computer science, resource contention refers to a conflict that arises when multiple entities attempt to access a shared resource, like random access memory, disk storage, cache memory, internal buses, or external network devices.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Memory can be treated as a resource, but memory management is usually considered separately, primarily because memory allocation and deallocation is significantly more frequent than acquisition and release of other resources, such as file handles.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Memory managed by an *external* system has similarities to both (internal) memory management (since it is memory) and resource management (since it is managed by an external system).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Examples include memory managed via native code and used from Java (via Java Native Interface); and objects in the Document Object Model (DOM), used from JavaScript.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In both these cases, the memory manager (garbage collector) of the runtime environment (virtual machine) is unable to manage the external memory (there is no shared memory management), and thus the external memory is treated as a resource, and managed analogously.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, cycles between systems (JavaScript referring to the DOM, referring back to JavaScript) can make management difficult or impossible.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Lexical management, when applicable, allows a better separation of concerns and is less error-prone.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is correct if the intervening `...` code does not contain an early exit (`return`), the language does not have exceptions, and `open` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, it causes a resource leak if there is a return or exception, and causes an incorrect release of unacquired resource if `open` can fail.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] There are two more fundamental problems: the acquisition-release pair is not adjacent (the release code must be written far from the acquisition code), and resource management is not encapsulated – the programmer must manually ensure that they are always paired.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In combination, these mean that acquisition and release must be explicitly paired, but cannot be placed together, thus making it easy for these to not be paired correctly.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This ensures correct release even if there is a return within the body or an exception thrown.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Further, note that the acquisition occurs *before* the `try` clause, ensuring that the `finally` clause is only executed if the `open` code succeeds (without throwing an exception), assuming that "no exception" means "success" (as is the case for `open` in Python).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] While this ensures correct resource management, it fails to provide adjacency or encapsulation.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] There are many variations in the implementation, and there are also significantly different approaches.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] The most common approach to resource management across languages is to use unwind protection, which is called when execution exits a scope – by execution running off the end of the block, returning from within the block, or an exception being thrown.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This works for stack-managed resources, and is implemented in many languages, including C#, Common Lisp, Java, Python, Ruby, and Scheme.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] The main problems with this approach is that the release code (most commonly in a `finally` clause) may be very distant from the acquisition code (it lacks *adjacency*), and that the acquisition and release code must always be paired by the caller (it lacks *encapsulation*).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] An alternative, more imperative approach, is to write asynchronous code in direct style: acquire a resource, and then in the next line have a *deferred* release, which is called when the scope is exited – synchronous acquisition followed by asynchronous release.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This originated in C++ as the ScopeGuard class, by Andrei Alexandrescu and Petru Marginean in 2000, with improvements by Joshua Lehrer, and has direct language support in D via the `scope` keyword (ScopeGuardStatement), where it is one approach to exception safety, in addition to RAII (see below).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] It has also been included in Go, as the `defer` statement.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This approach lacks encapsulation – one must explicitly match acquisition and release – but avoids having to create an object for each resource (code-wise, avoid writing a class for each type of resource).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In object-oriented programming, resources are encapsulated within objects that use them, such as a `file` object having a field whose value is a file descriptor (or more general file handle).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This allows the object to use and manage the resource without users of the object needing to do so.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, there is a wide variety of ways that objects and resources can be related.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Firstly, there is the question of ownership: does an object *have* a resource?
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Most common is to acquire a resource during object creation, and then explicitly release it via an instance method, commonly called `dispose`.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is analogous to traditional file management (acquire during `open`, release by explicit `close`), and is known as the dispose pattern.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is the basic approach used in several major modern object-oriented languages, including Java, C# and Python, and these languages have additional constructs to automate resource management.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, even in these languages, more complex object relationships result in more complex resource management, as discussed below.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] A natural approach is to make holding a resource be a class invariant: resources are acquired during object creation (specifically initialization), and released during object destruction (specifically finalization).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII), and ties resource management to object lifetime, ensuring that live objects have all necessary resources.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Other approaches do not make holding the resource a class invariant, and thus objects may not have necessary resources (because they've not been acquired yet, have already been released, or are being managed externally), resulting in errors such as trying to read from a closed file.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This approach ties resource management to memory management (specifically object management), so if there are no memory leaks (no object leaks), there are no resource leaks.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] RAII works naturally for heap-managed resources, not only stack-managed resources, and is composable: resources held by objects in arbitrarily complicated relationships (a complicated object graph) are released transparently simply by object destruction (so long as this is done properly!).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Firstly, because resources are expensive, it is desirable to release them promptly, so objects holding resources should be destroyed as soon as they become garbage (are no longer in use).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] However, most modern automatic memory management is non-deterministic, making no guarantees that objects will be destroyed promptly or even at all!
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is because it is cheaper to leave some garbage allocated than to precisely collect each object immediately on its becoming garbage.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Secondly, releasing resources during object destruction means that an object must have a *finalizer* (in deterministic memory management known as a *destructor*) – the object cannot simply be deallocated – which significantly complicates and slows garbage collection.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] When multiple objects rely on a single resource, resource management can be complicated.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] A fundamental question is whether a "has a" relationship is one of *owning* another object (object composition), or *viewing* another object (object aggregation).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] A common case is when one two objects are chained, as in pipe and filter pattern, the delegation pattern, the decorator pattern, or the adapter pattern.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] If the second object (which is not used directly) holds a resource, is the first object (which is used directly) responsible for managing the resource?
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is generally answered identically to whether the first object *owns* the second object: if so, then the owning object is also responsible for resource management ("having a resource" is transitive), while if not, then it is not.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Further, a single object may "have" several other objects, owning some and viewing others.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Both cases are commonly found, and conventions differ.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In object aggregation, nothing needs to be done by the viewing object, as it is not responsible for the resource.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Java Class Library, `Reader#close()` closes the underlying stream, and these can be chained.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] For example, a `BufferedReader` may contain a `InputStreamReader`, which in turn contains a `FileInputStream`, and calling `close` on the `BufferedReader` in turn closes the `InputStreamReader`, which in turn closes the `FileInputStream`, which in turn releases the system file resource.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] By contrast, in Python, a csv.reader does not own the `file` that it is reading, so there is no need (and it is not possible) to close the reader, and instead the `file` itself must be closed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] Various mechanisms exist to allow greater control of resource management.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Google Closure Library, the `goog.Disposable` class provides a `registerDisposable` method to register other objects to be disposed with this object, together with various lower-level instance and class methods to manage disposal.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] In structured programming, stack resource management is done simply by nesting code sufficiently to handle all cases.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This requires only a single return at the end of the code, and can result in heavily nested code if many resources must be acquired, which is considered an anti-pattern by some – the *Arrow Anti Pattern,* due to the triangular shape from the successive nesting.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] One other approach, which allows early return but consolidates cleanup in one place, is to have a single exit return of a function, preceded by cleanup code, and to use goto to jump to the cleanup before exit.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/resource-management-computing] This is infrequently seen in modern code, but occurs in some uses of C.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] For manufacturing, as TCO is typically compared with doing business overseas, it goes beyond the initial manufacturing cycle time and cost to make parts.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO includes a variety of cost of doing business items, for example, ship and re-ship, and opportunity costs, while it also considers incentives developed for an alternative approach.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Incentives and other variables include tax credits, common language, expedited delivery, and customer-oriented supplier visits.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO, when incorporated into a financial benefit analysis, provides a cost basis for determining the total economic value of an investment.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include: return on investment, internal rate of return, economic value added, return on information technology, and rapid economic justification.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] The roots of this concept date at least back to the first quarter of the twentieth century.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Many different methodologies and software tools have been developed to analyze TCO in various operational contexts.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis includes total cost of acquisition and operating costs, as well as costs related to replacement or upgrades at the end of the life cycle.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis is used to gauge the viability of any capital investment.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] An enterprise may use it as a product/process comparison tool.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] It is also used by credit markets and financing agencies.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO directly relates to an enterprise's asset and/or related systems total costs across all projects and processes, thus giving a picture of the profitability over time.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO analysis was popularized by the Gartner Group in 1987.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO is applied to the analysis of information technology products, seeking to quantify the financial impact of deploying a product over its life cycle.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] These technologies include software and hardware, and training.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] In the case of comparing TCO of existing versus proposed solutions, consideration should be put toward costs required to maintain the existing solution that may not necessarily be required for a proposed solution.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include cost of manual processing that are only required to support lack of existing automation, and extended support personnel.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Total cost of ownership can be applied to the structure and systems of a single building or a campus of buildings.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Pioneered by Doug Christensen and the facilities department at Brigham Young University starting in the 1980s, the concept gained more traction in educational facilities in the early 21st century.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] A key objective of planning, constructing, operating, and managing buildings via TCO principals is for building owners and facility professionals to predict needs and deliver data-driven results.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO can be applied any time during the life of a facility asset to manage cost inputs for the life of the structure or system into the future.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA, an ANSI Accredited Standards Developer, published *APPA 1000-1 – Total Cost of Ownership for Facilities Asset Management (TCO) – Part 1: Key Principles* as an American National Standard in December 2017.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-1 provides financial officers, facility professionals, architects, planners, construction workforce, and operations and maintenance (O&M) personnel the foundation of a standardized and holistic approach to implementing TCO key principles.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Implementation of TCO key principles can improve decision making, maximizing financial strategies over the life of an asset, starting at the planning and design stage and extends to the end of the asset's life.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-2, slated for publication in 2019, will focus on implementation and application of key TCO principals in facility management.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] The TCO concept is easily applicable to the transportation industry and to motor vehicle ownership, for example, the TCO defines the cost of owning an automobile from the time of purchase by the owner, through its operation and maintenance to the time it leaves the possession of the owner.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Comparative TCO studies between various models help consumers choose a car to fit their needs and budget.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] For personal vehicles in the United States, AAA's annual *Your Driving Costs* study estimated the average total cost of new-vehicle ownership at $11,577 per year in 2025, driven by depreciation, financing, fuel, insurance, maintenance, and license fees.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] In the truck industry, TCO is an essential factor for truck fleet managers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] By calculating the Total Cost of Ownership of a truck, the truck manager obtains a price per kilometer that varies according to fuel costs, the purchase price, and the resale price of the truck.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] If the truck is financed, the TCO also varies according to the interest rate on the loan.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] These factors in the trucking industry allow managers to make a clearer choice about which truck to select for their truck fleet, because when a transportation company wants to acquire 1 to 10 trucks, TCO is an essential factor to consider for the company's cash flow.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO does not assess how well a solution offers value for money, or how well it fits with an organisation's strategic objectives.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/total-cost-of-ownership] Some TCO analyses may include social and environmental costs but this is not always the case.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] This repackaging of computing services became the foundation of the shift to "on demand" computing, software as a service and cloud computing models that further propagated the idea of computing, application and network as a service.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] There was some initial skepticism about such a significant shift.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] However, the new model of computing caught on and eventually became mainstream.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] IBM, HP and Microsoft were early leaders in the new field of utility computing, with their business units and researchers working on the architecture, payment and development challenges of the new computing model.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Google, Amazon and others started to take the lead in 2008, as they established their own utility services for computing, storage and applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Utility computing can support grid computing which has the characteristic of very large computations or sudden peaks in demand which are supported via a large number of computers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] "Utility computing" has usually envisioned some form of virtualization so that the amount of storage or computing power available is considerably larger than that of a single time-sharing computer.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Multiple servers are used on the "back end" to make this possible.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] These might be a dedicated computer cluster specifically built for the purpose of being rented out, or even an under-utilized supercomputer.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] The technique of running a single calculation on multiple computers is known as distributed computing.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] The term "grid computing" is often used to describe a particular form of distributed computing, where the supporting nodes are geographically distributed or cross administrative domains.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] To provide utility computing services, a company can "bundle" the resources of members of the public for sale, who might be paid with a portion of the revenue from clients.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] One model, common among volunteer computing applications, is for a central server to dispense tasks to participating nodes, on the behest of approved end-users (in the commercial case, the paying customers).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Another model, sometimes called the virtual organization (VO), is more decentralized, with organizations buying and selling computing resources as needed or as they go idle.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] The definition of "utility computing" is sometimes extended to specialized tasks, such as web services.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Utility computing merely means "Pay and Use", with regards to computing power.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Utility computing is not a new concept, but rather has quite a long history.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] IBM and other mainframe providers conducted this kind of business in the following two decades, often referred to as time-sharing, offering computing power and database storage to banks and other large organizations from their worldwide data centers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] To facilitate this business model, mainframe operating systems evolved to include process control facilities, security, and user metering.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] The advent of mini computers changed this business model, by making computers affordable to almost all companies.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] As Intel and AMD increased the power of PC architecture servers with each new generation of processor, data centers became filled with thousands of servers.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] In the late 1990s utility computing re-surfaced.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] InsynQ, Inc. launched [on-demand] applications and desktop hosting services in 1997 using HP equipment.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] In 1998, HP set up the Utility Computing Division in Mountain View, California, assigning former Bell Labs computer scientists to begin work on a computing power plant, incorporating multiple utilities to form a software stack.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Services such as "IP billing-on-tap" were marketed.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] HP introduced the Utility Data Center in 2001.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Sun announced the Sun Cloud service to consumers in 2000.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] In December 2005, Alexa launched Alexa Web Search Platform, a Web search building tool for which the underlying power is utility computing.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Alexa charges users for storage, utilization, etc.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] There is space in the market for specific industries and applications as well as other niche applications powered by utility computing.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] The Database Utility and File Serving Utility enable IT organizations to independently add servers or storage as needed, retask workloads to different hardware, and maintain the environment without disruption.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] In spring 2006 3tera announced its AppLogic service and later that summer Amazon launched Amazon EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud).
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] These services allow the operation of general purpose computing applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Both are based on Xen virtualization software and the most commonly used operating system on the virtual computers is Linux, though Windows and Solaris are supported.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/utility-computing] Common uses include web application, SaaS, image rendering and processing but also general-purpose business applications.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] This whitepaper focuses on the cost optimization pillar of the Amazon Web Services (AWS) Well-Architected Framework.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] It provides guidance to help customers apply best practices in the design, delivery, and maintenance of AWS environments.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] A cost-optimized workload fully utilizes all resources, achieves an outcome at the lowest possible price point, and meets your functional requirements.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] This whitepaper provides in-depth guidance for building capability within your organization, designing your workload, selecting your services, configuring and operating the services, and applying cost optimization techniques.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] The AWS Well-Architected Framework helps you understand the decisions you make while building workloads on AWS.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] The Framework provides architectural best practices for designing and operating reliable, secure, efficient, cost-effective, and sustainable workloads in the cloud.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] It demonstrates a way to consistently measure your architectures against best practices and identify areas for improvement.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] We believe that having well-architected workloads greatly increases the likelihood of business success.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] This paper focuses on the cost optimization pillar, and how to architect workloads with the most effective use of services and resources, to achieve business outcomes at the lowest price point.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] You’ll learn how to apply the best practices of the cost optimization pillar within your organization.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] Cost optimization can be challenging in traditional on-premises solutions because you must predict future capacity and business needs while navigating complex procurement processes.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] This paper is intended for those in technology and finance roles, such as chief technology officers (CTOs), chief financial officers (CFOs), architects, developers, financial controllers, financial planners, business analysts, and operations team members.
[src:cost-optimization-cloud/welcome] This paper does not provide implementation details or architectural patterns, however, it does include references to appropriate resources.
